chart.name: Exercise 2: Example

publishLabelOptions.displayName: % change from last week in calls/day per acct
publishLabelOptions.label: C

chart.programText:
A = data('sf.org.num.awsServiceCallCount', filter=filter('namespace', 'AWS/CloudWatch'),rollup='rate').sum(by=['aws_account_id']).sum(over='1d').publish(label='A', enable=False)
B = (A).timeshift('1w').publish(label='B', enable=False)
C = ((A-B)/B).scale(100).publish(label='C')

options.markdown: For each exercise below, copy the chart and paste it to your own dashboard.

This chart has a metric in it that describes the number of calls that Splunk makes to the Amazon API on the customerâ€™s behalf. This info is important because when customers integrate Splunk with CloudWatch, they often have questions about why their AWS bill may have gone up. Itâ€™s also important for larger customers because Amazonâ€™s default rate limit is set pretty low. 

Iâ€™ve gone ahead and filtered the chart to show just calls to the CloudWatch API, but I havenâ€™t done anything else. 

Copy the Exercise 1 chart to your own dashboard.

Edit the chart on your dashboard so that it answers the following question: How many CloudWatch calls is Splunk making in total for each of my AWS accounts?

This is an example dashboard solution for "Help me analyze my API performance", from Analytics Workshop. Using the data provided in the charts to the right, answer the following questions: 
1. Is activity balanced across my servers and datacenters?
1. Is request volume changing?
1. Is request latency ok right now? 
1. Are all customers seeing the same latency?
1. What proportion of requests is coming from each customer? 


Tick the following boxes (one chart can satisfy multiple requirements):

chart.description: A and B have some dimension in common, but each has several other dimensions that are not shared. Analytics does not automatically know which dimension to use to relate plot A to plot B.

chart.programText:
A = data('cpu.utilization').publish(label='A', enable=False)
B = data('CPUUtilization', filter=filter('stat', 'count'),rollup='rate').publish(label='B', enable=False)
C = (A/B).publish(label='C')

chart.description: A and B have some dimension in common, and Analytics can match points in plot A to points in plot B.
chart.name: success
chart.programText:
A = data('cpu.utilization').sum(by=['AWSUniqueId']).publish(label='A', enable=False)
B = data('CPUUtilization', filter=filter('stat', 'count'),rollup='rate').publish(label='B', enable=False)
C = (A/B).publish(label='C')

chart.name: Bonus: Union of CPUUtilization and cpu.utilization
chart.programText:
A = data('cpu.utilization').max(by=['aws_instance_id']).publish(label='A', enable=False)
B = data('CPUUtilization', filter=filter('stat', 'mean')).max(by=['aws_instance_id']).publish(label='B', enable=False)
C = union(A,B).publish(label='C')
